        <div class="blog-article-body">

            <p class="blog-lead">
                Tax season means juggling W-2s, 1099s, mortgage interest
                statements, donation receipts, and more — usually as a pile
                of separate PDFs and scanned images. Combining them into one
                organized file makes handing everything to your accountant,
                or filing yourself, much faster.
            </p>

            <h2>Why combine tax documents into one file</h2>
            <ul>
                <li>One attachment to email your accountant instead of a dozen</li>
                <li>Easier to review the full picture before filing</li>
                <li>Simpler to archive a complete year's records in one place</li>
                <li>Avoids missing documents that get lost across separate emails or downloads</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>Step-by-step: Combine your tax documents</h2>
            <ol>
                <li>Gather all documents — PDFs from employers/banks and scanned receipts or images</li>
                <li>Convert any photos or scanned images to PDF first using <a href="/jpg-to-pdf">JPG to PDF</a></li>
                <li>Go to <a href="/merge-pdf">PdfToolStack Merge PDF</a></li>
                <li>Upload all documents and drag to reorder them logically (income documents first, then deductions/receipts)</li>
                <li>Merge and download the combined PDF</li>
            </ol>

            <h2>A sensible order for the combined file</h2>
            <ol>
                <li>Income documents — W-2s, 1099-NEC, 1099-MISC, 1099-INT/DIV</li>
                <li>Mortgage and property — 1098 mortgage interest, property tax statements</li>
                <li>Deductions and credits — donation receipts, medical expense receipts, education statements (1098-T)</li>
                <li>Prior year return, if your accountant needs it for reference</li>
            </ol>
            <p>
                Keeping a consistent order year over year also makes it
                faster for your accountant (or future you) to find a specific
                document.
            </p>

            <h2>Compress before sending if it's a large file</h2>
            <p>
                Years with a lot of scanned receipts can produce a large
                combined PDF. If it's too big to email, run it through
                <a href="/compress-pdf">PDF Compressor</a> before sending —
                text and numbers stay sharp, only embedded images are
                downsampled.
            </p>

            <h2>Protect the file before sending</h2>
            <p>
                Tax documents contain Social Security numbers, income, and
                bank details. If you're emailing the combined PDF, add a
                password with <a href="/lock-pdf">Lock PDF</a> and share the
                password through a separate channel like a text message
                rather than the same email thread.
            </p>

